      {
        "id": 1691982,
        "name": "Howard Davis",
        "username": "Howard_Davis",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/howard_davis/{size}/1982_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-06-21T20:04:39.000Z",
        "cooked": "<ul>\n<li>\n<a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/note.asp?iWine=1864444&amp;iNote=5065459\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\"><strong>1967 Giovannini Moresco Barbaresco Pajore</strong></a> <em>- Italy, Piedmont, Langhe, Barbaresco (6/21/2015)</em><br>\nPietro, the son of the winemaker, very generously brought two bottles of his father\u2019s wine to a dinner in Piemonte organised by our friend Jeff Chilcott of Marchesi di Gr\u00e9sy. A stable, quite pale colour. Both bottles were in great shape: the palate on the first better and bouquet on the second a little brighter and fresher. Both had a beautiful fragrance with notes like cigar, strawberries, spices, \u00c9poisses, Christmas cake, dried Autumn leaves, Rugiens rust etc etc. I\u2019d be happy sniffing this wine for hours \u2026 A beautiful, poignant tertiary palate. Complex with mellow flavours of preserved cherries, strawberries, dried herbs, pipe tobacco and that glazed Christmas cake. Multi-layered. Not at all musty, in fact vibrant with fresh acidity. Powerful with silky, fully resolved tannins. There seemed no immediate danger of either of these bottles falling over in the next few years. Grapes from the vineyard now go into the Gaja blend, Jeff said. One of my Wines of the Year. Thanks very much Pietro!</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>Posted from <a href=\"http://www.cellartracker.com/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">CellarTracker</a></em></p>",
